<seg id="750">& dot; algorithm, the standard for directional graphs. it produces hierarchical or layered graphs of directed graphs. the algorithm places the edges in the same direction (from top to bottom or from left to right) and then tries to produce as short edges and as few edge overlaps as possible.</seg>
<seg id="751">The & neato; algorithm is the default for unfinished graphs. it produces representations in accordance with the jump spring model. the Kamada Kawai algorithm is used, which is equivalent to statistical multi-dimensional scaling.</seg>
<seg id="752">The & FDP; algorithm creates a springle model layout for unfinished graphs. it uses the Fruchterman pure gold heuristic, and includes a multiple grid trigger for treating large and clustered graphs.</seg>
<seg id="753">The & Circo; algorithm ranks the nodes in a circular shape according to the description of Six und Tollis, 1999, and Kauffman and Wiese, 2002. it is useful for specific diagrams of multiple cyclic structures.</seg>
