<seg id="1043">& Povray; uses a technique called anti-aliasing to decrease the impact of these errors. generally, pictures with this property look better.</seg>
<seg id="1044">If you turn on anti-aliasing, calculate and connect & Povray; more than one beam per pixel. this technique means super-sampling.</seg>
<seg id="1045">& Povray; supports two methods of super-sampling. the standard is an adaptive, non-recursive method; adaptive because the super-sampling refers to the adjacent pixels. the second method is adaptive-recursive; recursively because each pixel is again and again divided and adaptive because the recursion depth depends on the calculated values.</seg>
<seg id="1046">If you choose the first method, POV-Ray tracks a beam per pixel. if the difference between color values exceeds the given threshold, then both pixels are processed by tracking a certain additional number of pixels with super-sampling. if you set the depth to 4, a grid of 4x4 additional points will be calculated, with a depth of 5 then 5x5 (25) additional beams per pixel.</seg>
<seg id="1047">The difference between two pixels is calculated as follows: R 1, g 1 and b 1 are the values for red, green and blue of the first pixel, r 2, g 2 and b 2 are the values for red, green and blue of the second pixel. the difference is then:</seg>
<seg id="1048">Diff = abs (r 1 -r 2) + abs (g 1 -g 2) + abs (b 1 -b 2)</seg>
<seg id="1049">The recursive method starts with 4 beams per pixel. if the difference between the color values exceeds the given threshold, then the pixel is divided into 4 subpixels, which can be followed individually and tested for further subdivisions. the maximum depth of the recursion can be set with the depth value.</seg>
